{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-07 17:56:05.897","ownerUserId":"88","body":"&lt;p&gt;You can use them both interchangeably, they basically mean the same thing, although &lt;em&gt;scordare&lt;/em&gt; may also be referred to an instrument that is out of tune.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Despite the fact that people believe &lt;em&gt;scodare&lt;/em&gt; is less formal than &lt;em&gt;dimenticare&lt;/em&gt;, it is not in fact exclusively part of any regional vocabulary and each region applies its own peculiarities to this verb when in use.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;For further reading on this matter, please &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.accademiadellacrusca.it/it/lingua-italiana/consulenza-linguistica/domande-risposte/scordare-dimenticare&quot;&gt;refer to this page&lt;/a&gt; on the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.accademiadellacrusca.it/it&quot;&gt;Accademia della Crusca&lt;/a&gt; website.&lt;/p&gt;","score":5,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 17:56:05.897","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":87}
{"commentCount":8,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-08 10:04:46.97","ownerUserId":"8","body":"&lt;p&gt;Yes, they have the same meaning and both could be used in your examples.&lt;br&gt;Nonetheless, there is a little difference in the meaning due to their Latin origins.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;dimenticare&lt;/em&gt; comes from the word &lt;em&gt;mens, mentis&lt;/em&gt; (mind) with the prefix &lt;em&gt;de-&lt;/em&gt; (distance). To forget something would be &lt;em&gt;to get it out of one's mind&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;scordare&lt;/em&gt; comes from the word &lt;em&gt;cor&lt;/em&gt; (heart) with the prefix &lt;em&gt;s-&lt;/em&gt; (meaning again distance or cancellation). To forget something would be &lt;em&gt;to get it out of one's heart&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;That's why you can say &lt;em&gt;ho dimenticato/scordato il tuo viso&lt;/em&gt; but you would usually say &lt;em&gt;il primo amore non si scorda mai&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;","score":9,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 18:57:30.147","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":88}
{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-30 11:44:45.473","ownerUserId":"12","body":"&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Si tratta di oggetti &lt;strong&gt;alquanto&lt;/strong&gt; strani.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Si tratta di oggetti &lt;strong&gt;parecchio&lt;/strong&gt; strani.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Does &lt;em&gt;alquanto&lt;/em&gt; refer to a less, equal or greater quantity in comparison to &lt;em&gt;parecchio&lt;/em&gt;?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Are the objects in the first sentence less, equal or more strange than the objects in the second one?&lt;/p&gt;","score":4,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 19:22:45.923","viewCount":95,"title":"Does &quot;alquanto&quot; express a greater quantity than &quot;parecchio&quot;?","tags":"&lt;word-choice&gt;","answerCount":4,"acceptedAnswerId":93,"postTypeId":1,"id":89}
{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-07 20:09:46.617","ownerUserId":"22","body":"&lt;p&gt;The meaning overlaps out of a great deal, but &lt;em&gt;alquanto&lt;/em&gt; would refer to a slightly smaller quantity with respect to &lt;em&gt;parecchio&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;So,&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alquanto + adjective&lt;/strong&gt; describes a value in the middle of the adjective, tending to it;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Parecchio + adjective&lt;/strong&gt; is a stronger assessment, which can be translated with &quot;very + adjective&quot;.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;","score":2,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 20:09:46.617","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":90}
{"commentCount":1,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-30 11:44:45.473","ownerUserId":"63","body":"&lt;p&gt;When used as adjective, &lt;em&gt;alquanto&lt;/em&gt; could mean that something is less than &lt;em&gt;parecchio&lt;/em&gt;, or it is equivalent to &lt;em&gt;parecchio&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Aveva bevuto alquanto vino.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;As adverb, it means &lt;em&gt;parecchio, non poco&lt;/em&gt;; as undefined pronoun, it means &lt;em&gt;un po'&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Oggi sto alquanto meglio.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Con alquanto di buon vino e di confetto il riconfortò. —G. Boccaccio&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;","score":2,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 20:13:28.667","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":91}
{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-07 20:26:15.903","ownerUserId":"8","body":"&lt;p&gt;From the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.accademiadellacrusca.it/it/lingua-italiana/consulenza-linguistica/domande-risposte/avverbi-quantit&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Accademia della Crusca explanation&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;le forme &lt;em&gt;abbastanza, alquanto e piuttosto&lt;/em&gt; risultano sinonimiche, in  quanto si definiscono reciprocamente.   La tendenza al rafforzamento  semantico si può inoltre notare nella forma &lt;em&gt;alquanto&lt;/em&gt;, derivata dal  latino &lt;em&gt;aliquăntu(m)&lt;/em&gt; che indicava una quantità discreta, spesso  traducibile in italiano con &lt;em&gt;un po'&lt;/em&gt;. Il Dizionario Etimologico della  Lingua Italiana definisce infatti il valore avverbiale di questa forma  con «un poco», osservando nella sezione etimologica: «Alquanto nel  sign. di 'molto' è errore biasimato dal G. Gherardini, Voci italiane  ammissibili benché proscritte dall'elenco del sig. Bernardoni (Milano,  1812).   Considerando che il Grande dizionario italiano dell'uso  impiega il termine &lt;em&gt;parecchio&lt;/em&gt; per definire questa forma avverbiale, è  quindi possibile ipotizzarne l'uso in senso intensivo, specie per  rafforzare un aggettivo (ad es.: &quot;ti vedo alquanto stanco&quot; =  'parecchio, molto stanco').&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;To sum up: The words &lt;em&gt;abbastanza, alquanto, parecchio, piuttosto&lt;/em&gt; are synonyms and could be used to define each other. However, the etymology of &lt;em&gt;alquanto&lt;/em&gt; (from the Latin word, meaning &quot;un po' - few, a small quantity&quot;) makes it closer to &lt;em&gt;abbastanza&lt;/em&gt; rather than to &lt;em&gt;tanto&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;br&gt;At the same time, &lt;em&gt;parecchio&lt;/em&gt; is usually defined as &quot;a bit less than a lot&quot;:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Parecchio&lt;/strong&gt; C’è parecchia, anzi molta confusione intorno a questa voce. E quando si è detto &lt;em&gt;parecchia anzi molta&lt;/em&gt; si è già spiegato tutto o quasi tutto. Al pari di &lt;em&gt;assai&lt;/em&gt; (e non mettiamo nel mucchio altra roba come &lt;em&gt;abbastanza&lt;/em&gt;, sennò facciamo soltanto confusione), &lt;em&gt;parecchio è meno di molto, equivale a piú che sufficiente, in quantità notevole, ma non è ancora molto&lt;/em&gt; (Scrivendo e parlando di  Luciano Satta, Firenze, Sansoni, 1988, p. 177)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;","score":5,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 20:17:00.87","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":92}
{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-07 20:21:13.253","ownerUserId":"17","body":"&lt;p&gt;I'd translate the two sentences as&lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Si tratta di oggetti &lt;strong&gt;alquanto&lt;/strong&gt; strani&lt;br&gt;  &lt;em&gt;We are talking about &lt;strong&gt;rather&lt;/strong&gt; strange objects&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;and &lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Si tratta di oggetti &lt;strong&gt;parecchio&lt;/strong&gt; strani&lt;br&gt;  &lt;em&gt;We are talking about &lt;strong&gt;very&lt;/strong&gt; strange objects&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;So, &lt;strong&gt;parecchio&lt;/strong&gt; is stronger than &lt;strong&gt;alquanto&lt;/strong&gt; and it literally indicates a bigger quantity.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;That being said, as a native speaker I would never use &lt;strong&gt;alquanto&lt;/strong&gt; in a sentence, as it doesn't sound very colloquial. I'd go with &lt;strong&gt;un po'&lt;/strong&gt;, which could be roughly translated to English as &lt;strong&gt;a little&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;","score":5,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 20:21:13.253","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":93}
{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2014-01-02 22:14:40.853","ownerUserId":"12","body":"&lt;p&gt;I often hear people saying &quot;due euro&quot;, even if &quot;due euri&quot; should be used.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Can anyone explain which one is correct, maybe adding a comment in reference to the differences in regional usage?&lt;/p&gt;","score":6,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 20:42:57.657","viewCount":116,"title":"&quot;due euro&quot; vs. &quot;due euri&quot;","tags":"&lt;plural&gt;","answerCount":5,"postTypeId":1,"id":94}
{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-07 21:06:07.597","ownerUserId":"63","body":"&lt;p&gt;In English, the following sentences have a different meaning.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;If I were rich, I would live on Long Island.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;If I am late, it is because the bus is late.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;While the first sentence is using the irrealis mood, and it expresses something that will never happen (I will never be rich, and I will never live on Long Island), the second sentence is expressing a possibility (in the case I am late, that is because the bus is late).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Is there a way to express that also in Italian? Can I express the difference there is in those English sentences also in Italian, using two different moods or tenses?&lt;/p&gt;","score":2,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 20:46:08.42","viewCount":37,"title":"Irrealis conditional versus possibility","tags":"&lt;tenses&gt;&lt;usage&gt;","answerCount":1,"acceptedAnswerId":101,"postTypeId":1,"id":95}
{"commentCount":10,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-07 21:22:34.187","ownerUserId":"63","body":"&lt;p&gt;Can I use the future tense to express a possibility, or predict the future, rather than saying something I will surely do?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;For example, if I say &lt;em&gt;andrò a casa di mio cugino&lt;/em&gt; (literally, &quot;I will go to my cousin's house&quot;), does that mean I am surely going to my cousin's house, or is that also understood as &quot;there is a possibility I will go to my cousin's house&quot;?&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;To make another example, in English &quot;I will come to live in Italy&quot; can express something I am willing to do, not something I surely going to do; for some circumstances, the person saying that sentence could not be able to come to live in Italy, for example because she cannot sell her house.&lt;br&gt;What mood or tense should I use in that case, in Italian?&lt;/p&gt;","score":5,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 20:52:16.12","viewCount":121,"title":"Using the Simple Future to express a possibility","tags":"&lt;tenses&gt;&lt;usage&gt;","answerCount":2,"acceptedAnswerId":102,"postTypeId":1,"id":96}
{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2014-01-02 22:14:40.853","ownerUserId":"63","body":"&lt;p&gt;The plural of &lt;em&gt;euro&lt;/em&gt; is &lt;em&gt;euro&lt;/em&gt;; I think that was established by the &lt;em&gt;Accademia della Crusca&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Sometimes, you hear the plural being used, and often it is done in a semi-serious tone; in other cases, it is done from people who are used to use the plural for currency names (which what normally happens; compare &lt;em&gt;un dollaro&lt;/em&gt; with &lt;em&gt;dieci dollari&lt;/em&gt;), and does the same for &lt;em&gt;euro&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;h3&gt;References&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linguistic_issues_concerning_the_euro#Italian&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;Linguistic issues concerning the euro&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;","score":9,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 20:58:14.263","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":97}
{"commentCount":5,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-07 21:00:24.297","ownerUserId":"22","body":"&lt;p&gt;Italian has a future tense only in the Indicative mood, and Indicative is the mood of certainty, when you don't add specific verbs whose effect is to add uncertainty.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;So, no, you can't use that sentence to express a probability. If you want to achieve this effect (convey uncertainty), you say:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;  &lt;p&gt;Credo che andrò a casa di mio cugino.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;So, the verb &quot;credere&quot; here adds that particular feature you want: you think you're going to your cousin's house, but that's not certain. &lt;/p&gt;","score":1,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 21:00:24.297","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":98}
{"commentCount":0,"lastActivityDate":"2013-11-07 21:01:17.807","ownerUserId":"8","body":"&lt;p&gt;I second @kiamlaluno's answer. The Accademia della Crusca &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.accademiadellacrusca.it/en/italian-language/language-consulting/questions-answers/plurale-euro&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;explains&lt;/a&gt; that the correct plural form of &lt;em&gt;euro&lt;/em&gt; is &lt;em&gt;euro&lt;/em&gt; (claiming that it was actually the EU decision from 1998 to make exceptions for the plural form of &lt;em&gt;euro&lt;/em&gt; in English, German, and Italian).&lt;/p&gt;","score":1,"creationDate":"2013-11-07 21:01:17.807","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":99}
