{"commentCount":5,"lastActivityDate":"2014-06-08 22:40:00.29","ownerUserId":"193","body":"&lt;p&gt;In Italian &quot;j&quot; is pronounced like a semi consonant &quot;i&quot; when it occurs between vowels or at the beginning of a word (e.g. &quot;Ajaccio&quot;, &quot;Jacopo&quot;); otherwise it is pronounced like an &quot;i&quot; when it occurs at the end of a word, typically as the plural of some words ending in &quot;-io&quot; (&quot;varj&quot;, plural of &quot;vario&quot;) (&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/j/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;1&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://forum.accademiadellacrusca.it/forum_10/interventi/4737.shtml.html&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;2&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;As Rmano pointed out, an alternative to &quot;j&quot; for the plural of some words ending in &quot;-io&quot; is &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/plurale-dei-nomi-in-io_%28La_grammatica_italiana%29/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;circumflex &quot;î&quot;&lt;/a&gt;. The use of &quot;j&quot; is more ancient than &quot;î&quot; but today they are both not much in use anymore (anyway, I still like the use of &quot;î&quot;, I think it is still considered erudite Italian and it still has its function).&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Note that Italian &quot;y&quot; is pronounced just as &quot;i&quot; (&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/y/&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;3&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;","score":5,"creationDate":"2014-06-08 00:10:23.877","title":"","tags":"","postTypeId":2,"id":2012}
